Chicken 'n sausage nightshade soup. (Never to be recreated.)

This started with a variety of leftovers from an Asian soup restaurant. The soups were good. We ended up pouring all the different leftover broth into a cup and took it home.

This was the first generation.

I took the broth mix, added a bunch of cooked rice to it. More chicken stock and a couple Costco cans of chicken meat (With broth), Some peppers, and about 1/2 onion? And made a soup with it.

That was the second generation.

Last night there was a little of the rice, broth & chicken left over. Maybe a small portion? But getting pretty dry by now. Julie & I chatted about what to do with the leftovers while driving around in Grrr.

In the fridge..
There were two slices of bacon, falling out of the package.
Half of a big 'Ol Andouille sausage.
A paseo pepper.
About 4 Fresno peppers.
Half an onion.
Part of a bunch of Celery, gettin' a little.. Floppy. Still ok.

Chopped up the bacon, tossed in frying pan. When that was about 1/2 done..
Chopped up the Andouille sausage and tossed that in the pan as well. 
Found (1) hot dog. Chopped it up fin and tossed it in as well.
Fried all of this meat up to get a base of flavorful oil.

Spooned out the meat into the soup pot, leaving all that tasty oil.

Dumped in the chopped up veggies. Started them frying. Added salt, pepper, pig BBQ seasoning, chili powder & cumin. Fried all this 'till the veggies were pretty much done Added one big 'ol crushed clove of garlic.

Added in some chicken stock to deglaze the pan and get the garlic & veggies to blend into almost a sauce.

This all went into the soup pot.

Added one can of tomato sauce to the pot
Added one can of chopped tomatoes to the pot.
Added a quart or maybe even more chicken stock to the pot.
Added two more cans of Costco chicken with broth to the pot. (Needed more)
Get this all heated up together.

By now I have this very spicy, somewhat harsh, tomato and pepper based soup.

Then I went WAY out on a limb, and added a can of sweetened condensed milk.

This left us with about 6 quarts of the most wonderful creamy ambrosia.. That I'll never be able to recreate ever again.

So, we're enjoying it while it lasts.

So tasty, so sad.







